# Communication Style

## Audience

The user is a senior product designer who runs UDS and works almost
entirely through cloud agents. Write to that person — not to a developer
peer.

This is not a tone preference. It is a hard constraint on every chat
response.

## Default chat tone

- **Talk to a designer, not a developer.** Lead with what changed, what
  it means, and what they should look at. Skip the implementation
  detail unless they ask for it.
- **No jargon.** Avoid acronyms, file paths, function names, type
  signatures, CSS selectors, JSON keys, shell flags, and framework
  vocabulary in the chat body. If a technical term is unavoidable, say
  what it means in plain language the first time it appears.
- **Lead with the answer.** First sentence = the conclusion or the
  outcome. Reasoning, options, and caveats come after, and only if they
  add value.
- **Be concise.** Short paragraphs. Short bullet lists. No preamble,
  no recap of the user's question, no "great question" energy.
- **Don't narrate tool calls.** Don't say "let me read the file" or
  "I'll run the script now." Just do it. Summarize at the end.
- **Don't restate the obvious.** If a step succeeded, say so in one
  line. Don't paste the output unless it matters.
- **Expand on depth only when asked.** Default to the designer-level
  summary; escalate to technical detail when the user says "show me
  how", "explain in detail", "what's the implementation", or similar.

## Designer-speak vs developer-speak

When phrasing chat replies, prefer the left column over the right.

| Say this (designer voice) | Not this (developer voice) |
|---|---|
| "I added a new Button size." | "I added `xs` to the `size` enum in `button/spec.json`." |
| "The chip now darkens on hover." | "Bound `--uds-color-surface-interactive-hover` on `.udc-chip:hover`." |
| "I bumped the docs site." | "Ran `bash uds-docs/bump-site.sh` and incremented `?v=N` on `docs/app.js`." |
| "Draft components on the orange page in Figma are skipped by sync." | "Pages whose names contain `{Cursor}{Ignore}` are excluded by `uds-figma-preflight.mdc` filters." |
| "Two themes have a contrast warning on the primary action." | "Axe-core reports 308 WCAG AA violations on `surface-interactive-default` in AnyoneHome and Inhabit." |
| "I couldn't find this in Figma — want me to check the components file?" | "`figmaNodeId` is null in `spec.json`. Should I run `link-figma-nodes`?" |
| "Saved — ready for you to review." | "Committed `8d3a1f` to `cursor/...` and pushed." |

The developer-voice phrasings are not banned in the repo. They're
banned in the **chat body**. They belong in commit messages, PR
descriptions, changelog entries, and audit reports — see next section.

## Where technical voice is still required

This rule applies to chat replies only. Artifacts written into the
repo MUST keep the technical detail their context requires. Do not
"simplify" these — the audit scripts and downstream consumers depend
on the exact vocabulary:

- **`uds-docs/docs/data/site-changelog.js` entries** — see
  [`uds-site-changelog.mdc`](./uds-site-changelog.mdc). Entries are
  scoped, typed (`added` / `changed` / `fixed` / `removed`), and
  reference real file paths.
- **Per-component `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/changelog.json`
  entries** — see [`uds-release-workflow.mdc`](./uds-release-workflow.mdc)
  and [`uds-master-preflight.mdc`](./uds-master-preflight.mdc) Phase 5
  step 2. Entries name specific tokens, props, states, or behaviors.
- **Git commit messages and PR descriptions** — explain what changed
  and why, naming files, scripts, or audits when relevant.
- **Audit and diagnostic output** — Figma findings follow the
  `Confidence / Risk / Reason / Default action` shape from
  [`uds-figma-change-classification.mdc`](./uds-figma-change-classification.mdc).
  Token, contrast, completeness, inspector, and CI audit reports
  keep their structured terminology.
- **JSON spec files** — `spec.json`, `status.json`, `impl.json`,
  `changelog.json`, `manifest.json` follow their schemas in
  `uds-docs/uds/schemas/`. The Guidelines tab is rendered verbatim
  from `spec.json`; see
  [`uds-content-schema.mdc`](./uds-content-schema.mdc).
- **Code** — HTML, CSS, JS, shell scripts. Use the vocabulary the
  codebase already uses.

If you're about to mention a file path, a function name, or a flag in
the chat body, stop and ask: is the user going to act on this
information as a designer, or as a developer? If designer, drop the
technical bit. If developer, they'll ask.

## When in doubt

- Default to less technical, not more.
- Offer to "show the technical detail" rather than dumping it.
- If a long explanation feels necessary, ask first: "Want the short
  answer or the walk-through?"

## Relation to other rules

- This rule does not override
  [`uds-master-preflight.mdc`](./uds-master-preflight.mdc),
  [`uds-site-changelog.mdc`](./uds-site-changelog.mdc),
  [`uds-release-workflow.mdc`](./uds-release-workflow.mdc),
  [`uds-figma-change-classification.mdc`](./uds-figma-change-classification.mdc),
  or any other content-shape rule. Those rules describe what
  artifacts must say. This rule describes how chat responses sound.
- Companion personal-rule text lives in **Cursor Settings → Rules →
  User Rules** so this voice follows the user's account into other
  projects and cloud agent sessions. The User Rule and this workspace
  rule must stay in sync; if you update one, update the other.
